        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Men over 50 should aim for 30 to 40 grams of protein per meal — slightly higher than the often-cited 25 to 30 gram baseline. After 50, anabolic resistance means your body needs a stronger per-meal stimulus to trigger the same muscle protein synthesis response. The exact target depends on body weight: roughly 0.24 grams per pound per meal is the research-supported threshold."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "Is 30 grams of protein per meal enough after 50?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "30 grams per meal is a solid practical target for most men over 50 — close to the threshold needed to maximally trigger muscle protein synthesis. For heavier men (185 pounds or more) or those doing regular resistance training, 35 to 40 grams per meal is more appropriate. 30 grams is the right floor, not the ceiling."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "What happens if you eat too little protein per meal?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Meals with less than 20 grams of protein often fail to trigger a meaningful muscle protein synthesis response, particularly in men over 50. Small protein doses spread thinly across many small meals are less effective than fewer, larger protein feedings. The per-meal threshold matters as much as the daily total."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "Can you absorb more than 30 grams of protein in one meal?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Yes — your body can digest and absorb significantly more than 30 grams per meal. The 30 gram figure refers to the amount needed to maximally stimulate muscle protein synthesis, not the absorption limit. Protein beyond that threshold is not wasted — it is used for other functions or oxidized for energy."
        }
      },
