    <h2>The Three Mistakes That Kill Per-Meal Results</h2>

    <p>
      Most men who aren't getting results from their protein intake are making one of three per-meal errors. These are consistent patterns — worth recognizing if any of them sound familiar.
    </p>

    <div class="mistake-card">
      <div class="mc-label">Mistake 01</div>
      <div class="mc-title">Spreading protein too thin across too many small meals</div>
      <div class="mc-body">The idea that eating six small meals a day maximizes muscle protein synthesis has been largely debunked. If each of those six meals contains only 15 to 20 grams of protein, most of them fall below the effective threshold for triggering a meaningful anabolic response. Frequency without sufficient dose per meal doesn't work — and after 50, the dose requirement is higher, not lower.</div>
      <div class="mc-fix">Three to four meals at 30–40 grams each outperforms six small meals at 15–20 grams each, every time.</div>
    </div>

    <div class="mistake-card">
      <div class="mc-label">Mistake 02</div>
      <div class="mc-title">Low-protein breakfast undermining the whole day</div>
      <div class="mc-body">Breakfast is the meal where most men over 50 fall furthest below their per-meal target — often eating 8 to 12 grams when the target is 35 to 40. Starting the day below threshold means the first muscle protein synthesis signal of the day never fires properly. The remaining meals then have to compensate, and most men never fully close that gap by dinner.</div>
      <div class="mc-fix">Fix breakfast first. Hit 30–40g before 9am and the rest of the day becomes significantly easier to manage. See <a href="/blog/high-protein-breakfast-men-over-50/" style="color:var(--green);font-weight:600;">7 high-protein breakfast options</a> that take under 3 minutes.</div>
    </div>

    <div class="mistake-card">
      <div class="mc-label">Mistake 03</div>
      <div class="mc-title">"I hit my daily total but I'm still not seeing results"</div>
      <div class="mc-body">This is the most common frustrating pattern — a man hitting 120 to 130 grams daily but seeing limited results. Often the explanation is distribution: 10 grams at breakfast, 20 at lunch, 80 at dinner. The daily total looks correct. But the per-meal distribution means the anabolic signal fires weakly in the morning, moderately at lunch, and once strongly at dinner. That's one effective signal per day instead of three or four.</div>
      <div class="mc-fix">Audit distribution, not just totals. If most of your protein arrives at dinner, that's the variable to fix.</div>
    </div>

    <h2>Hit the Total. Hit the Meals. Everything Works.</h2>

    <p>
      The full picture is actually simple once you see it laid out. Two variables, both within your control:
    </p>

    <div class="anchor-callout">
      <p>Daily total: 0.7–1.0g per pound.<br />Per meal: ~0.24g per pound.<br />Repeat 3–4 times per day.</p>
    </div>

    <p>
      If both of those are consistently in range, you've done what the research supports for muscle preservation after 50. Everything else — <a href="/blog/protein-timing-after-40/" style="color:var(--green);font-weight:600;">timing</a>, food sources, supplements — is refinement on top of that foundation.
    </p>

    <p>
      The practical shortcut: if your bodyweight is in the 160 to 185 pound range, aim for 35 to 40 grams per meal. If you're lighter, 30 to 35 grams is likely your effective threshold. If you're heavier, push toward 40 to 50 grams per meal. Round numbers, applied consistently, beat precise calculations applied inconsistently every time.
    </p>

